  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For Jozachar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jozacar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the son of Shimeath, and Jehozabad the son of Shomer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] In 2 Chron. the names of the conspirators are given as ‘Zabad the son of Shimeath an Ammonitess, and Jehozabad the son of Shemrith a Moabitess’. Between ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "זבד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Zabad and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "זכר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Zacar, the abbreviated form of Jozacar, it is easy to see how a mistake might arise from the similarity of the Hebrew letters. The Chronicler who mentions the nationality of the mothers gives their names both in the feminine form. In Kings the last two letters from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "שׁמרית",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Shemrith) have fallen out and so the name has become ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "שׁמר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Shomer). Although these names are without doubt historical it is very remarkable (as Thenius points out) how when they are translated they recall Zechariah’s last words ‘The Lord look upon it and require it’. For they signify ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jehovah-remembers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’, the son of ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hearer;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’ and ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jehovah-gives",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’, the son of ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Watcher",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and they buried him with his fathers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. In the city of David, but as the Chronicler records, not in the sepulchres of the kings. The words of the Chronicler about the ‘greatness of the burdens’ laid upon Jehoash refers to the many prophetic oracles which were uttered against him in consequence of his evil deeds. Cf. for that sense of the word ‘burden’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 13:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and many other passages of that prophet. On the margin R.V. in such cases, gives ‘oracle concerning’.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and Amaziah his son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The Chronicler (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 24:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") speaks of the ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Jehoash’; we know nothing however of any son but Amaziah, though it is said (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 24:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ‘Jehoiada took for Jehoash two wives, and he begat sons and daughters’.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For Jozachar the son of Shimeath",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; called in Chronicles \"Zabad,\" probably through a corruption of the text. His mother, Shimeath, was, according to Chronicles (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 24:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), an Ammonitess. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Jehozabad the son of Shomer.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " For \"Shomer\" we have in Chronicles \"Shim-rith,\" which is the feminine form of \"Shomer,\" and we are told that she was a Moabitess. The Jews were at all times fond of taking wives from Moab and Ammon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ruth 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 9:1, 2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 13:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), despite the prohibition of mixed marriages in the Law (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "His servants, smote him, and he died",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (for their motives, see the introductory paragraph), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and they buried him with his fathers in the city of David.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Some critics (as Thenius and Dean Stanley) see a contradiction between this statement and that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 24:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that he was \"not buried in the sepulchers of the kings;\" but, as Bertheau, Keil, and Bahr observe. \"the two statements are not irreconcilable,\" since he may have been regarded as \"buried with his fathers,\" if his grave was anywhere in Jerusalem, even though he was excluded from the royal burying-place. ",
        "children": []
      },
